##  ABI Compliance

2.  Write a program that uses only caller-save registers and the sp and ra registers, it must have a function called 'my_function' that receives three values and does the following:

    - Computes the sum of the first two values: `SUM 1`
    - Calls a function called `mystery_function` passing `SUM 1` and the first value as parameters in this order: `CALL 1`
    - Computes the difference between the second value and the returned value of the `mystery_function` (`CALL 1`): `DIFF 1`
    - Sums the third value to the difference (`DIFF 1`): `SUM 2`
    - Calls `mystery_function` again passing the sum above (`SUM 2`) and the second value as parameters in this order: `CALL 2`
    - Computes the difference between the third value and the returned value of the `mystery_function` above (`CALL 2`): `DIFF 2`
    - Sums the difference above (`DIFF 2`) with `SUM 2`: `SUM 3`
    - Returns `SUM 3`
    - The C code below exemplifies these steps

      ```c
      int my_function(int a, int b, int c){
      int aux = b - mystery_function(a+b, a) + c;
      return c - mystery_function(aux, b) + aux;
      };
      ```

    <a href="https://riscv-programming.org/ale/#select_url_" target="_blank">Assistant Link</a>

3.  Convert the following C function to assembly code. Note: `char` and `short` values are extended to 32 bits when stored in the program stack.

    ```c
    int operation(){
        int a = 1;
        int b = -2;
        short c = 3;
        short d = -4;
        char e = 5;
        char f = -6;
        int g = 7;
        int h = -8;
        char i = 9;
        char j = -10;
        short k = 11;
        short l = -12;
        int m = 13;
        int n = -14;
        return mystery_function(a, b, c, d, e, f, g, h, i, j, k, l, m, n);
    }
    ```
